00:25:06.580 --> 00:25:16.860
The benefit of working with a development editor, I think, is enough to offset some of the differences in revenue that you get, by our perspective.

00:25:16.860 --> 00:25:22.600
Yeah, and it also depends on how big your audience is that you can connect with to get the book, right?

00:25:22.600 --> 00:25:27.260
Like if, Stephen King could probably really easily self-publish a book and be fine.

00:25:27.260 --> 00:25:32.900
But if you've never written a book and you don't run a bunch of podcasts or something like this, it can be a challenge, right?

00:25:32.900 --> 00:25:40.600
Yeah, and then also to put in perspective the 37 Signals book, I mean, they had a huge following when they were publishing that.

00:25:40.600 --> 00:25:43.620
Signals versus noise was very large.

00:25:43.620 --> 00:25:44.660
And so.

00:25:44.660 --> 00:25:45.440
Yep, yep.

00:25:45.440 --> 00:25:48.260
I've had a lot of experience with this.

00:25:48.260 --> 00:25:53.540
And, I mean, first of all, it's important to understand how the publishing industry works.

00:25:54.040 --> 00:26:03.000
And there's about 10% of the books published kind of break even or make some profit.

00:26:03.000 --> 00:26:07.680
And about 1% of the books published are actual successes.

00:26:08.080 --> 00:26:17.980
So when you get involved with that, if you have a book that's a success, it's got to pay for the 90% of failures.

00:26:17.980 --> 00:26:27.880
So, and the publishing industry looks at these numbers and they tend to say, well, to get our numbers up, we just have to publish more books.

00:26:27.880 --> 00:26:32.660
They don't consider, should we try and make better books?

00:26:32.660 --> 00:26:37.920
And there are, of course, special cases and things like that where that's not the case.

00:26:37.920 --> 00:26:40.720
But in general, that's kind of how their numbers work.

00:26:40.720 --> 00:26:46.920
And so the other thing that you have to look at is, you know, what kind of commitment are they going to have?

00:26:46.920 --> 00:26:51.920
For the longest time, I wouldn't take, I wouldn't worry about the advance.

00:26:52.180 --> 00:27:03.100
And then, you know, after talking to people, I realized, actually, you want to push for the largest advance you can get because you want to put the publisher in financial jeopardy.

00:27:03.100 --> 00:27:08.520
Because that's what's going to stimulate them to go out and promote your book.

00:27:08.520 --> 00:27:13.220
And some publishers will try and promote a book for a few months.

00:27:13.220 --> 00:27:18.900
And then if it doesn't, you know, go gold, then they sort of drop it and they stop.

00:27:19.340 --> 00:27:22.100
There's all these pitfalls that you can get into.

00:27:22.100 --> 00:27:31.760
And you don't have control of your book anymore once you sign that contract unless you rewrite the contract, which they'll tell you that we know we don't do.

00:27:31.760 --> 00:27:33.300
But you can.

00:27:33.300 --> 00:27:36.520
You can always line through the contract and everything.

00:27:37.460 --> 00:27:45.640
So if you self-publish, you are then responsible for, as people have been saying, promoting your own books.

00:27:45.640 --> 00:27:48.540
And sometimes it works and sometimes it doesn't.

00:27:48.540 --> 00:27:57.700
But even when it doesn't work, you'll often get maybe more money than you would have just by taking in advance.

00:27:57.700 --> 00:27:58.080
Right.

00:27:58.120 --> 00:28:04.200
It's got to be basically like 10 times less good to do your self-publishing or something on that scale, right?

00:28:04.200 --> 00:28:05.800
Something on that scale.

00:28:05.800 --> 00:28:08.520
There's also the satisfaction of doing it yourself.

00:28:08.520 --> 00:28:16.560
And I'll point out one more thing, which is that now if you start talking to a publisher, even one that you've published with before,

00:28:16.720 --> 00:28:23.360
the first thing they'll do is send you this form that's asking you, how are you going to promote your book?

00:28:23.360 --> 00:28:24.360
Do you have a blog?

00:28:24.360 --> 00:28:25.640
Do you have a podcast?

00:28:25.640 --> 00:28:26.420
Do you have all these things?

00:28:26.420 --> 00:28:33.060
And when you look at that and you go, well, why am I working with you if I'm going to be promoting my book?

00:28:33.060 --> 00:28:35.320
You know, what are you bringing to the table?

00:28:35.620 --> 00:28:43.500
And these days, if they can't promote it, then you can pretty much do all the rest of the stuff yourself.

00:28:43.500 --> 00:28:52.260
And so unless they're wonderful promoters, you should really think seriously about what are you getting from the publisher.

00:28:52.260 --> 00:28:53.580
Yeah, that's really great advice.

