00:39:17.500 --> 00:39:22.560
But I wanted to say one thing that I actually tweeted some time ago.

00:39:22.560 --> 00:39:31.160
David M. Geary is the author of some famous Java graphics books and, more recently, an HTML5 canvas book.

00:39:31.160 --> 00:39:37.540
And he wrote, I think, in one of his prefaces, a recipe for writing a programming book.

00:39:37.540 --> 00:39:41.140
It also applies to blog, but it's really good.

00:39:41.140 --> 00:39:46.360
The recipe is, code is an interesting example illustrating an idea.

00:39:46.940 --> 00:39:48.480
And I think this is the key, right?

00:39:48.480 --> 00:39:51.960
I call this the example-driven approach of writing.

00:39:51.960 --> 00:39:55.520
So, you think of an interesting example that demonstrates an idea.

00:39:55.520 --> 00:39:57.120
Then you explain it.

00:39:57.120 --> 00:40:00.200
So, the text flows from the example.

00:40:00.200 --> 00:40:02.840
The text is there to explain the example.

00:40:02.840 --> 00:40:06.720
And the example is there, of course, to convey some ideas, some concepts.

00:40:06.720 --> 00:40:08.560
And then you just repeat.

00:40:08.560 --> 00:40:11.320
And I took this idea to heart.

00:40:11.320 --> 00:40:16.600
And I think one of the things that I'm proud of in Flint Python is I think it has interesting examples.

00:40:17.060 --> 00:40:18.060
Short but interesting.

00:40:18.060 --> 00:40:22.040
I don't like books that have a lot of full-bar examples, for instance.

00:40:22.040 --> 00:40:26.540
Flint Python has a few full-bar examples, but most of them are not full-bar examples.

00:40:26.540 --> 00:40:29.860
And it's hard, actually, to come up with good examples.

00:40:29.860 --> 00:40:33.300
But I think it's totally worth it to make the book interesting.

00:40:33.300 --> 00:40:34.720
And, of course, you can do that.

00:40:34.720 --> 00:40:35.400
Yeah, I agree.

00:40:35.400 --> 00:40:37.400
I don't like those fake examples either.

00:40:37.400 --> 00:40:39.080
I always feel like they're kind of a cop-out.

00:40:39.140 --> 00:40:43.340
I think it's good to be able to build from something into the book.

00:40:43.340 --> 00:40:50.800
So, in my case, I built on lots of presentations because I've been using Python and I've been evangelizing Python since 1998.

00:40:51.300 --> 00:40:57.800
So, I had a lot of presentations and a lot of course material over the years that were just slides and examples.

00:40:57.800 --> 00:41:00.320
So, a lot of that went into the book.

00:41:00.320 --> 00:41:14.740
So, I really think the idea of having some prior motivation to develop examples and write, like a blog or courses or podcasts or whatever, is a very good way of building up material to then launch into a book.

00:41:14.860 --> 00:41:15.440
Great advice.

00:41:15.440 --> 00:41:22.220
And you brought up the example of sort of almost a pattern for writing, a recipe for writing blogs and books.

00:41:22.220 --> 00:41:25.900
