And so, then I went into statistics and after that into journalism and then found my way back to computers.

00:43:57.320 --> 00:43:58.780
Yeah, how interesting.

00:43:58.780 --> 00:44:08.380
And I do find it really surprising that journalism and Python and programming actually intersect non-trivially these days compared to how it used to be, at least.

00:44:08.380 --> 00:44:15.920
There's more and more resources on just how do we combine this data journalism and storytelling all together.

00:44:16.080 --> 00:44:30.580
And I feel like data science is a very interesting intersection there because even as a data scientist, you also have to think about how you tell the story in the sense of how you report it to somebody that might be able to make some sort of actionable choices based on the data that you find.

00:44:30.920 --> 00:44:34.140
I also started in journalism in college.

00:44:34.140 --> 00:44:40.940
My first year, I was a journalism major and one of the best courses I had was taught by an editor from the LA Times.

00:44:40.940 --> 00:44:43.980
And he had us compose at the typewriter.

00:44:43.980 --> 00:44:46.160
That was his, that was the whole thing.

00:44:46.220 --> 00:44:51.560
And we started with, you know, a set of facts and I don't know, an hour and a half.

00:44:51.560 --> 00:44:58.820
And then he kept changing the time and reducing it, reducing it until it was like, I don't know, 15 or 20 minutes to write the story.

00:44:58.820 --> 00:45:01.460
And it was, it was super useful.

00:45:01.460 --> 00:45:03.420
Oh, that sounds really interesting.

00:45:03.420 --> 00:45:07.020
Bruce, go ahead and give us your thoughts on also getting into writing.

00:45:07.020 --> 00:45:12.620
Although being a journalism major, maybe you also have not so much of that experience.

00:45:12.620 --> 00:45:14.320
Well, I did it in high school.

00:45:14.320 --> 00:45:21.120
I was involved in journalism and studied in the first year and kind of realized it was just going to be more of the same thing.

00:45:21.120 --> 00:45:30.180
And so I changed to physics and got into physics and engineering and eventually computer engineering for my master's degree.

00:45:30.180 --> 00:45:37.480
But I kept being like, I kept showing up at the college newspaper and getting involved with there.

00:45:37.480 --> 00:45:41.220
So I guess I always had this impulse to do it.

00:45:41.220 --> 00:45:50.220
But I would say for people, in fact, at the last PyCon, I held a little open spaces for people who are interested in writing.

00:45:50.220 --> 00:45:57.860
And I'd say the, like a couple of the most important things that came out of that, I think I blogged about it.

00:45:57.860 --> 00:46:14.240
So the details are in the, in my blog, but probably the most important things that I think people like don't get taught are something called active voice, which a lot of people don't know what that means.

00:46:14.240 --> 00:46:19.260
It means more or less you're talking in the immediate tense.

00:46:19.260 --> 00:46:26.140
And it makes your sentences shorter and more direct and more connected to the reader.

00:46:26.140 --> 00:46:38.460
And the other thing, which was huge, someone told me this years ago, is once you think you're done with whatever it is, you know, your blog post or your chapter or whatever, is go back and read it aloud.

00:46:39.180 --> 00:46:47.520
And by reading it aloud, and that's every single word, and it takes a long time, but things will jump out at you.

00:46:47.520 --> 00:46:53.620
And it makes you realize that when you're reading quietly, you skip over stuff and you don't notice things.

00:46:54.140 --> 00:47:03.980
And by reading it aloud, it forces you to pay attention to every single word and the amount of rewriting that you will do when you do that process is kind of amazing.

00:47:04.620 --> 00:47:17.460
So most of my work now, I end up editing myself or like when I'm co-authoring the Kotlin book with a woman who's originally Russian and she speaks.

00:47:17.460 --> 00:47:20.480
Her English is good, but she has a hard time writing.

00:47:20.740 --> 00:47:26.180
And so originally, I was just going to kind of be the editor and publisher of this book.

00:47:26.180 --> 00:47:33.200
But now I'm kind of actively writing and rewriting and doing a lot of pretty heavy editing because of that.

00:47:33.200 --> 00:47:35.880
But, you know, that's just the way projects are.

00:47:35.880 --> 00:47:36.640
They change.

00:47:36.640 --> 00:47:38.120
They evolve.

00:47:38.120 --> 00:47:39.520
Yeah, that's really great advice.

00:47:39.520 --> 00:47:42.540
I like the active voice.

00:47:42.540 --> 00:47:44.540
Definitely a fan of that style of writing.

00:47:44.540 --> 00:47:47.180
That is the hardest thing to learn.

00:47:47.520 --> 00:47:53.180
And even when you know what it is, you will fall back to writing in passive voice and then you'll recover.

00:47:53.180 --> 00:48:03.460
The hardest thing in the world, I think, is just to understand what it is and to constantly be looking for places where you can change passive to active.

00:48:03.460 --> 00:48:04.060
Yeah, nice.

