Back when I was working on my math PhD, I wrote a lot of Latex as well.

00:52:49.340 --> 00:52:50.340
Bruce, how about you?

00:52:50.340 --> 00:52:58.280
I've done all the camera-ready pages since Thinking and C++ for my books, even the ones that were published through publishers.

00:52:59.260 --> 00:53:06.500
And because it would do all the indexing and table of contents, I didn't use page layout.

00:53:06.500 --> 00:53:07.700
I used Word.

00:53:07.700 --> 00:53:12.860
But I have switched over to using Pandoc-flavored Markdown.

00:53:12.860 --> 00:53:19.240
And I have a whole bunch of tools sets that I produce things from with that.

00:53:20.040 --> 00:53:21.560
And I use Sublime Text.

00:53:21.560 --> 00:53:36.860
But for the camera-ready pages, I'll probably go back to Word just because, I mean, I'll convert from the Markdown source to Word and then use it for layout because it still has kind of everything in it.

00:53:36.960 --> 00:53:39.720
And a regular page layout program doesn't do that.

00:53:39.720 --> 00:53:40.140
All right.

00:53:40.140 --> 00:53:40.380
Cool.

00:53:40.380 --> 00:53:40.800
Dan?

00:53:40.920 --> 00:53:48.540
I'm using two editors because I found that switching between two different environments, it really helps me just look at the text differently.

00:53:48.540 --> 00:53:50.640
And I often use different devices too.

00:53:50.640 --> 00:53:56.780
So I'll write something on my computer and then, you know, read it again by emailing it to myself on my phone, for example.

00:53:56.780 --> 00:53:59.940
And I just found that other things will jump out at me.

00:53:59.940 --> 00:54:04.140
But for the actual writing, I use a tool called Ulysses.

00:54:04.140 --> 00:54:06.760
I think it's macOS only.

00:54:06.760 --> 00:54:08.020
But it's really great.

00:54:08.020 --> 00:54:10.080
It's like a fancy Markdown editor.

00:54:10.860 --> 00:54:13.780
And I use that to do all of my writing for the newsletter and for the web.

00:54:13.780 --> 00:54:19.400
And then I do all of my editing in Sublime Text and then, yeah, publish from there.

00:54:19.400 --> 00:54:20.360
So I use these two.

00:54:20.360 --> 00:54:20.940
Very cool.

00:54:20.940 --> 00:54:21.360
Very cool.

00:54:21.360 --> 00:54:24.720
For my Markdown, I use IA Writer, which is a Mac thing as well.

00:54:24.720 --> 00:54:25.520
But I don't write any books.

00:54:25.520 --> 00:54:26.700
So, all right.

00:54:26.700 --> 00:54:28.420
So let's go ahead and wrap this up, you guys.

00:54:28.420 --> 00:54:31.240
And I will give you each a chance for a final call to action.

00:54:31.240 --> 00:54:33.000
Say, Dan, how about you?

00:54:33.000 --> 00:54:33.620
Final call to action.

