What do they do?

00:54:35.180 --> 00:54:35.940
Buy my book.

00:54:35.940 --> 00:54:38.140
No, I feel like that's too easy.

00:54:40.800 --> 00:54:42.260
But seriously, please do.

00:54:42.260 --> 00:54:44.820
They should buy and study your book.

00:54:44.820 --> 00:54:46.800
And then they want to write their own.

00:54:46.800 --> 00:54:49.040
Yeah.

00:54:49.040 --> 00:54:50.280
No, like I feel like the.

00:54:50.280 --> 00:54:50.940
Okay.

00:54:50.940 --> 00:54:54.260
So what would I would love the most besides people buying my book?

00:54:54.260 --> 00:54:55.660
No, I got to stop this.

00:54:55.660 --> 00:55:00.460
I think it would be great if more people went out there and just shared their experience.

00:55:00.460 --> 00:55:06.720
And, you know, please, for everyone listening, like don't feel bad about putting something out there that's not perfect.

00:55:06.720 --> 00:55:11.880
I mean, of course, you're going to get crappy comments and sometimes a little bit snarky feedback.

00:55:12.660 --> 00:55:13.780
But who cares?

00:55:13.780 --> 00:55:18.100
You know, it's that this is the first step and it can only get better from there.

00:55:18.100 --> 00:55:24.780
And you'll be glad when you look back at that, you know, a couple of months or years later and also what this can do for your software development career.

00:55:24.780 --> 00:55:30.240
So I encourage everyone just to go out there, you know, just put like a two or three hundred word program example.

00:55:30.240 --> 00:55:32.080
Put it on your blog or somewhere.

00:55:32.080 --> 00:55:34.240
It will be a great experience.

00:55:34.240 --> 00:55:34.580
Yeah.

00:55:34.580 --> 00:55:34.920
Nice.

00:55:34.920 --> 00:55:35.460
Bruce.

00:55:35.660 --> 00:55:38.020
And a lot of this is my experience with co-authors.

00:55:38.020 --> 00:55:50.200
I would say if you're thinking of writing a book or co-authoring a book, really do some deep, you know, soul searching and try and figure out why you want to do it.

00:55:50.200 --> 00:55:57.480
Because often in the process of writing the book or co-authoring the book, you'll find out what it really is.

00:55:57.480 --> 00:56:14.960
And if it isn't actually in alignment with finishing the book or if you're hoping to be famous or, you know, make a lot of money or and it doesn't mean that like you might want to write a book that promotes your consulting business around a certain topic.

00:56:14.960 --> 00:56:16.180
And that makes sense.

00:56:16.180 --> 00:56:31.740
But know that that's what you're doing before you dive into this project, because if you don't really understand it, what what it is that you want, you might be thinking, oh, well, if I write this book, then I will get what I want.

00:56:31.740 --> 00:56:37.840
And the book probably won't let you do that.

00:56:37.840 --> 00:56:42.040
You may not finish if if it's if it's not really in line with what you want.

00:56:42.040 --> 00:56:42.300
Yeah.

00:56:42.300 --> 00:56:42.720
Good advice.

00:56:42.720 --> 00:56:43.200
Luciano.

00:56:43.200 --> 00:56:55.580
Well, I agree that force yourself or make yourself write or produce content, maybe not in writing, but like maybe slides for talks at a local meetup and teach stuff to people.

00:56:55.580 --> 00:56:57.880
There's always people willing to learn.

00:56:58.180 --> 00:57:15.540
So if you can connect, for instance, to a local hackerspace or makerspace or a similar place, a community place where you can go and teach courses for free, that's going to improve a lot your communication skills and also give you motivation to develop material.

00:57:16.000 --> 00:57:27.320
And the other thing I want to say is if you're going to publish something on the internet, please don't do it on Medium or Facebook or, you know, any of those big platforms that are eating the web.

00:57:27.320 --> 00:57:28.960
Have your own site.

00:57:28.960 --> 00:57:35.780
If it's too expensive for you to have your own domain, share it with a few friends, you know, and just put a simple tool.

00:57:35.920 --> 00:57:38.980
I love DocuWiki, for instance, it's super simple to install.

00:57:38.980 --> 00:57:43.240
And I'm really happy with my two websites that I created with that.

00:57:43.240 --> 00:57:48.620
So do it, but do it on your own site and not, you know, feeding one of those monsters.

00:57:48.620 --> 00:57:50.240
That's really interesting advice.

00:57:50.240 --> 00:57:52.120
And I generally agree with you for sure.

00:57:52.120 --> 00:57:53.360
Catherine?

00:57:53.780 --> 00:57:56.120
I think there's been a lot of great advice shared.

00:57:56.120 --> 00:58:09.180
I think particularly like if you're a junior person or you're starting to learn, let's say you're self-taught, or if you have some imposter syndrome, you come from an underrepresented group in tech.

00:58:09.180 --> 00:58:17.140
I think writing can really help reaffirm that you do actually have quite a large grasp on quite a lot of topics.

00:58:17.920 --> 00:58:24.040
And I recently read an article, I'll share it so you can put it in the links, about how I hacked my imposter syndrome.

00:58:24.040 --> 00:58:24.820
That's awesome.

00:58:24.820 --> 00:58:34.560
And the person went through and essentially every day they would write, you know, some sort of problem they were having debugging with, I believe they work in data science or machine learning.

00:58:34.560 --> 00:58:38.920
And they would end up writing through their mental process and then what they learned.

00:58:38.920 --> 00:58:41.980
And I think these types of things would be great blog posts.

00:58:41.980 --> 00:58:45.660
They show that you're learning and growing as a data scientist.

00:58:46.300 --> 00:58:53.960
And this is something that, you know, you can look back on your body of work after a long period of time, whether you want to post it publicly or have it privately.

00:58:53.960 --> 00:58:57.860
And really just show, wow, I have learned so much.

00:58:57.860 --> 00:59:01.220
And my grasp is so large now after so much time.

00:59:01.220 --> 00:59:06.080
I think this is a really good practice even just to do outside of the publishing realm.

00:59:06.080 --> 00:59:06.800
Yeah, very nice.

00:59:06.800 --> 00:59:07.520
Brian?

00:59:07.520 --> 00:59:10.740
There's a lot of different styles of writing, and I think that's great.

00:59:11.140 --> 00:59:16.780
And people think that just practice is going to make you better, but you also have to learn.

00:59:17.020 --> 00:59:32.220
So like other art forms like drawing, take a blog post or an author that you like their writing style and try to teach something that you know in the style of somebody you admire and just try out different styles and see what fits for you.

00:59:32.220 --> 00:59:33.840
I think that's a good way to start.

00:59:33.840 --> 00:59:35.000
Yeah, that's great advice.

00:59:35.440 --> 00:59:40.020
So I'll leave everyone with one book recommendation that kind of ties some of this stuff together.

00:59:40.020 --> 00:59:45.000
There's this really interesting book called Hustle, the Life-Changing Effects of Constant Motion.

00:59:45.640 --> 00:59:54.140
And it's this book by Jesse Tevilove, who wrote this book about just like always seizing the moment and always just be working on something.

00:59:54.140 --> 00:59:57.460
And the reason this is relevant is he is writing a book.

00:59:57.460 --> 00:59:59.060
Writing a book was taking him years.

00:59:59.060 --> 01:00:00.300
Like, I need some money to survive.

01:00:00.300 --> 01:00:02.600
I'm going to try to write a book the opposite of a year.

01:00:02.600 --> 01:00:12.840
And so he wrote a 192-page book that is pretty well done in, I think, three days and published it from the time he opened the editor till the time it was on Amazon was seven days.

01:00:12.840 --> 01:00:19.580
And it's really inspiring, even if you don't care about authoring a book, just like, oh, my gosh, what can you do if you really like powered through a project?

01:00:19.580 --> 01:00:20.300
It's pretty cool.

01:00:20.300 --> 01:00:21.740
So people check that out.

